VISUAL RHYTHM — FOLLOW THE PLAN'S CLASSIFICATION
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

The plan from Part A has already classified every beat as ⚡ / 🔄 / 🫁.
You follow that classification. Do NOT reclassify.

─────────────────────────────────────────────
TYPE 1 — ⚡ POWER MOMENTS (Multiple images, fast visual change)
─────────────────────────────────────────────
  Follow the split count from the Split Plan.
  Each sub-beat = its own distinct situation.
  IMAGE DURATION: 1-3 seconds per image (handled by automation tool)

─────────────────────────────────────────────
TYPE 2 — 🔄 NORMAL MOMENTS (Single image, moderate hold)
─────────────────────────────────────────────
  One image per beat. Shows the explanatory or transitional situation.
  IMAGE DURATION: 4-8 seconds (handled by automation tool)

─────────────────────────────────────────────
TYPE 3 — 🫁 BREATHING MOMENTS (Single image, longer hold)
─────────────────────────────────────────────
  One powerful image per beat. Let it sit.
  IMAGE DURATION: 5-10 seconds (handled by automation tool)

RHYTHM PATTERN (from the plan):
  ⚡⚡⚡🔄⚡⚡🫁⚡⚡⚡🔄🔄⚡⚡🫁
  NOT all fast. NOT all slow. The MIX is what hooks viewers.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
FLOATING TEXT RULE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

  Internal thoughts, questions, and feelings CAN be shown as
  floating text near the character's head.

  GOOD USE:
    → "Am I accepted?" floating above character looking at group
    → "was that stupid?" floating above character after speaking
    → "they're angry at me" floating above character reading a text
    → "I'm too much" floating above character alone after conflict

  Keep floating text SHORT — 2-5 words maximum.
  Only use when it adds emotional clarity to the situation.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
VISUAL VARIETY RULE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

  Even within situation-based visuals, vary the scenes.
  Same emotion can happen in different situations:

  "feeling invisible" could be:
    → Sitting at lunch table no one talking to
    → Waving at someone who doesn't notice
    → Being talked over in a conversation
    → Standing in group photo but no one standing near
    → Sending message, seeing "read" but no reply

  NEVER use the same situation twice for the same emotion.
  No two consecutive scenes should look visually similar.

